        "value": [
            {
                "spanType": "span-simple-text",
                "text": "There have been five big mass extinctions in Earth's history – these are called the 'Big Five'. Understanding the reasons and timelines of these events is important to understand the speed and scale of species extinctions today."
            }
        ],
        "parseErrors": []
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "value": [
            {
                "spanType": "span-simple-text",
                "text": "When and why did these mass extinction events happen?"
            }
        ],
        "parseErrors": []
    },
    {
        "type": "heading",
        "level": 3,
        "text": {
            "spanType": "span-simple-text",
            "text": "What is a mass extinction?"
        },
        "parseErrors": []
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "value": [
            {
                "spanType": "span-simple-text",
                "text": "First, we need to be clear on what we mean by ‘mass extinction’. Extinctions are a normal part of evolution: they occur naturally and periodically over time.{ref}Jablonski D (1986) "
            },
            {
                "spanType": "span-link",
                "children": [
                    {
                        "spanType": "span-simple-text",
                        "text": "Mass and background extinctions: the alternation of macroevolutionary regimes"
                    }
                ],
                "url": "https://science.sciencemag.org/content/231/4734/129.abstract?casa_token=EoFixpArJnsAAAAA:R4ejNN9Ccy8BjYWiJJMfWUToj6qJSJFQ8jWGiMsL_x2OoBRfsrBdze0p8n6kvYdps25LiL8hcRKwrcy9"
            },
            {
                "spanType": "span-simple-text",
                "text": ". "
            },
            {
                "spanType": "span-italic",
                "children": [
                    {
                        "spanType": "span-simple-text",
                        "text": "Science"
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "spanType": "span-simple-text",
                "text": " 231:129–133{/ref} "
            }
        ],
        "parseErrors": []
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "value": [
            {
                "spanType": "span-simple-text",
                "text": "There’s a natural background rate to the timing and frequency of extinctions: 10% of species are lost every million years; 30% every 10 million years; and 65% every 100 million years.{ref}Raup DM (1991) "
            },
            {
                "spanType": "span-link",
                "children": [
                    {
                        "spanType": "span-simple-text",
                        "text": "A kill curve for Phanerozoic marine species"
                    }
                ],
                "url": "https://www.jstor.org/stable/2400988?casa_token=TqXeuHQvy4sAAAAA:gx18YNQDflE4PaS7Ipj9LGKadOiFL0MZzXbLJEkVQ-ASBEXXr58T-b0Y1uZoFeIoqxjNYCzYSH9qoblVQLfMccmJSU-FMr70W1L-bcgSF99Rxu-oDHxRqA"
            },
            {
                "spanType": "span-simple-text",
                "text": ". "
            },
            {
                "spanType": "span-italic",
                "children": [
                    {
                        "spanType": "span-simple-text",
                        "text": "Paleobiology"
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "spanType": "span-simple-text",
                "text": ". 17:37–48.{/ref} It would be wrong to assume that species going extinct is out of line with what we would expect. Evolution occurs through the balance of "
            },
            {
                "spanType": "span-italic",
                "children": [
                    {
                        "spanType": "span-simple-text",
                        "text": "extinction"
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "spanType": "span-simple-text",
                "text": " – the end of species – and "
            },
            {
                "spanType": "span-italic",
                "children": [
                    {
                        "spanType": "span-simple-text",
                        "text": "speciation"
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "spanType": "span-simple-text",
                "text": " – the creation of new ones."
            }
        ],
        "parseErrors": []
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "value": [
            {
                "spanType": "span-simple-text",
                "text": "Extinctions occur periodically at what we would call the ‘background rate’. We can therefore identify periods of history when extinctions were happening much faster than this background rate – this would tell us that there was an additional environmental or ecological pressure creating more extinctions than we would expect. "
            }
        ],
        "parseErrors": []
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "value": [
            {
                "spanType": "span-simple-text",
                "text": "But "
            },
            {
                "spanType": "span-italic",
                "children": [
                    {
                        "spanType": "span-simple-text",
                        "text": "mass extinctions"
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "spanType": "span-simple-text",
                "text": " are defined as periods with "
            },
            {
                "spanType": "span-italic",
                "children": [
                    {
                        "spanType": "span-simple-text",
                        "text": "much"
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "spanType": "span-simple-text",
                "text": " higher extinction rates than normal. They are defined by both magnitude and rate. Magnitude is the percentage of species that are lost. Rate is how quickly this happens. These metrics are inevitably linked, but we need both to qualify as a mass extinction."
            }
        ],
        "parseErrors": []
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "value": [
            {
                "spanType": "span-simple-text",
                "text": "In a mass extinction at least 75% of species go extinct within a relatively (by geological standard) short period of time.{ref}We can actually see a 75% reduction in species in two ways: high extinction rates, or very low speciation rates. If speciation – the creation of new species – slows down a lot, the extinction rate does not need to be as high as we would expect in order to deplete species numbers by 75%. These events are sometimes called ‘mass depletions’ but are treated in the same way as mass extinctions.{/ref} Typically less than two million years."
            }
        ],
        "parseErrors": []
    },
    {
        "type": "heading",
        "level": 3,
        "text": {
            "spanType": "span-simple-text",
            "text": "The ‘Big Five’ mass extinctions"
        },
        "parseErrors": []
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "value": [
            {
                "spanType": "span-simple-text",
                "text": "There have been five mass extinction events in Earth’s history. At least, since 500 million years ago; we know very little about extinction events in the Precambrian and early Cambrian earlier which predates this.{ref}Jenkins RJF (1989) The supposed terminal Precambrian extinction event in relation to the Cnideria. Memoirs of the Association of Australasian Paleonotologist 8:307–317.{/ref} These are called the ‘Big Five’, for obvious reasons."
            }
        ],
        "parseErrors": []
    },
